<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration wants to 
bar blind or deaf passengers or passengers whose handicaps make them 
unable to open an airliners emergency exit door from sitting in the 
exit row seats 
the proposed rule to be published monday on the eve of a senate 
hearing on discrimination against the blind in air travel has 
already brought criticism from the national federation of the blind 
and a handicapped veterans group 
this proposal is both silly and discriminatory and well 
resist it mark maurer president of the federation said 
wednesday 
i feel crummy about it said james gashel the federations 
government affairs director who was ejected from a united airlines 
plane by police last year in chicago after refusing to leave an exit 
door seat 
but faa spokesman john leyden called the matter a critical 
safety issue and said people in those seats have an added 
responsibility 
the faa says that seating people who wouldnt be able to operate 
the emergency exit door in other rows of the aircraft enhances 
their safety as well as that of other passengers 
the air transportation association which represents airlines 
said the rule is needed to provide uniform procedures for airlines 
rules on exit door seating vary among the airlines said spokeswoman 
leslie roland 
don mcguire spokesman for braniff airlines said handicapped 
people on braniff flights are asked not to sit in seats next to 
exits but are allowed to if they insist american airlines spokesman 
jim brown said the carrier already bars exit door seating to women 
close to giving birth handicapped people or children 
an faa rulemaking notice said handicapped people often believe 
the airlines have no right to refuse them seats by the exit a 1986 
law guarantees the handicapped full access to air travel but allows 
the faa to impose seating restrictions for safety 
the proposed rule would limit exit row seating in domestic 
airliners to people who can open the doors and take other actions 
that will expedite the evacuation of an aircraft in an accident or 
other emergency 
the proposal would affect the seat locations of persons with 
physical and mental disabilities parents with small children obese 
and frail persons children traveling alone and others who can 
impede evacuation when seated in exit rows the faa said leyden 
said this would also include those who are blind or deaf or for any 
other reason might have difficulty operating the door 
in a way the people in those seats become auxiliary flight 
attendants leyden said they have to assess the situation look 
out the window to see if its safe to open the door there might be 
fire on the wing and then open the door and lead people to safety 
choosing the safest path 
the blind federations maurer said that in some cases an alert 
blind person might be the best passenger to have next to an exit 
door especially if the plane filled with smoke because that person 
would be used to being unable to see 
david capozzi an official of the paralyzed veterans of america 
said the faa rules would go too far and might prevent people in 
wheelchairs from boarding some commuter flights where the exit row 
might be the only one with enough room for them 
under the proposed rule each carrier would have to submit its 
procedures for faa approval it would take effect after a 90day 
period for public comment unless the faa sees reason to change it 
</TEXT>
