<TEXT>
a 78yearold snake researcher bitten by a 
deadly viper last week was released from the hospital and has 
returned to his laboratory 
william haast whose illness touched off an international effort 
to find antivenin to save him was released wednedsay 
he said the pakistani pit viper was only defending itself 
blaming the bite on his own carelessness it was the 148th time he 
had been bitten during his career as a researcher and the 19th time 
he was hospitalized 
they have a reputation for striking out he said wednesday 
they can reach out from the ground over two feet 
haast was bitten feb 28 because he did not expect the reaction 
to be as serious as it was he did not enter the university of utah 
health sciences center until the following day 
he was treated with antivenin flown in from california when it 
was discovered he was allergic to the serum on hand 
through the efforts of a white house aide more serums were 
obtained from england from the soviet union and even from private 
sources in iran but in the end the serums from overseas were not 
used because doctors feared possible side effects and because haast 
appeared to be recovering 
haast said the people who sent in the antivenins were the real 
heroes of this story 
he is director of the miami serpentarium laboratories at the 
university of utah he keeps an estimated 1000 poisonous snakes at 
the lab where venom is extracted for research and the manufacture 
of antivenins 
hospital spokesman john dwan said haast would still have to have 
blood tests every other day for the next week or so 
