<TEXT>
the state court of appeals has upheld a law 
denying a golf course property tax break to the prestigious burning 
tree club unless it accepts women as members 
the private club at bethesda in marylands washington suburbs has 
historically numbered congressmen cabinet officials and us 
supreme court justices among its members 
the tax break which applies to both state and county taxes 
allows clubs to pay a special rate by agreeing to maintain a golf 
course as open space and not use it for commercial or residential 
development 
the 1986 law on accepting women was declared unconstitutional 
july 22 1987 by anne arundel circuit judge martin a wolff 
because of a provision allowing clubs to exclude certain sexes on 
specific days or at specific times he said the entire law was 
invalid because that one section violated the states equal rights 
amendment 
the states highest court on wednesday agreed that the exemption 
allowing discrimination on certain days or certain times was 
unconstitutional but said that didnt invalidate the entire law 
as a result clubs accepting the preferential tax treatment will 
have to admit women and cant set aside times or days exclusively 
for men or women 
burning tree is the only maryland club maintaining a menonly 
membership policy that takes advantage of the property tax break 
court records showed that for the 198687 tax year burning tree 
saved about 300000 in state and local taxes under the open space 
tax exemption 
robert zarnoch an assistant state attorney general said other 
clubs in maryland claim the preferred tax rate while setting aside 
tee times for men or women 
james dunbar a lawyer who represented burning tree before the 
appeals court said he had not had time to read and digest the 52 
majority opinion and dissent and couldnt comment on whether there 
will be a further appeal 
</TEXT>
