<TEXT>
a major underground nuclear weapons test 
rocked the nevada desert at dawn today unleashing a shock felt atop 
some las vegas hotelcasinos 85 miles away authorities said 
the test carried a force of 20 to 150 kilotons the highest 
allowed under test limitation treaties and created a shock that 
registered 51 on the richter scale of ground motion all us tests 
are listed as either less than 20 kilotons or as 20 to 150 kilotons 
thirteen protesters demonstrated at the main entrance to the 
desert site and 11 were arrested for trespassing 
the test conducted at 605 am was 55 minutes earlier than 
originally scheduled to take advantage of more favorable wind 
conditions according to energy department spokesman jim boyer 
the test codenamed ingot was the third conducted at the nevada 
test site this year the nuclear device was buried in a shaft 1600 
feet beneath the surface of yucca flat 
boyer speaking from a control point 15 miles from ground zero 
reported considerable ground motion at the time of detonation 
the seismograph needle is swinging wildly from side to side 
boyer said video cameras on the ground are getting quite a jolt 
the situation appears normal boyer said watching monitors 
at the control building it doesnt look like there were any 
problems whatsoever 
boyer said test controllers reported a subsidence at ground zero 
44 minutes after the blast a subsidence or ground collapse is a 
favorable sign because it indicates the test cavity has been sealed 
preventing any leak of radioactive gases 
motion from the blast was recorded by monitors atop some 
highrise hotelcasinos in las vegas but telephone operators at the 
resorts reported receiving no calls from guests inquiring about the 
blast 
waverly person a spokesman at the national earthquake 
information center in golden colo said the 51 richter scale 
reading was not as high as some previous tests the richter scale is 
a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake a quake magnitude 
of 5 can cause considerable damage in a populated area 
the test was the 690th announced shot since testing began in 
nevada in january 1951 twelve tests were conducted in 1988 it was 
conducted under the sponsorship of lawrencelivermore laboratories 
