<TEXT>
a harvard professor has disputed the contention 
of two leading surgeons that replacing intestines and other organs 
is a justifiable lastditch remedy for dying children even though 
it has never saved a child 
there must be some likelihood of success before the desperate 
remedy becomes more than a desperate search for an opportunity to 
try a new procedure awaiting trial dr francis d moore of 
harvard university wrote in an editorial in fridays journal of the 
american medical association 
the heads of two surgical teams that have performed the nations 
only four and fiveorgan abdominal transplants defended their 
efforts in separate articles saying they found no evidence of organ 
rejection in their first four child patients even though they all 
died 
dr thomas e starzl of the university of pittsburgh and dr 
james w williams of rushpresbyterianst lukes medical center in 
chicago said they also found no indication of a potentially fatal 
reaction in which immune cells transplanted from the organ donor 
attack the recipients cells 
while lauding the leadership of starzl and williams moore 
questioned their assertion that severely ill children tolerate the 
operative procedure very well 
he noted that two of the four children died soon after the 
operation and said the other two had many complications 
if this is tolerating the operative procedure very well one 
wonders what it would look like if the procedures were not well 
tolerated moore said he called for further study with animals 
before more transplants are tried on children 
starzls first patient a 6yearold girl died a few hours after 
her 1983 transplant at childrens hospital of pittsburgh most of 
her small intestine had been sucked out by a swimming pool pump and 
she later developed liver failure she received those organs along 
with a new spleen and pancreas 
his second patient survived longer than any of the three others 
tabatha foster 3 of madisonville ky died of cancer of the lymph 
system in may six months after receiving a new liver pancreas 
stomach small intestine and part of a large intestine 
the most important conclusion from our longest surviving 
patient was that she came tantalizingly close to truly longterm 
survival with a functioning gastrointestinal tract starzl said 
it seems inevitable that further cautious trials of 
multiorgan transplants will be made he said 
like tabatha both of williams patients were born with short gut 
syndrome a deformity that leads to liver failure 
williams first patient a 17monthold boy lived three days 
after surgery in 1986 he died of sudden internal bleeding his 
other patient a 10monthold boy died of cancer 3 months after 
receiving a new liver pancreas small bowel and part of the stomach 
in 1988 
doctors believe the cancer that killed tabatha and the other 
child last year resulted from too much antirejection medication 
which suppresses the bodys immune system 
williams said he performed his two multiorgan transplants 
because of the hopelessness of the childrens condition 
the forbidding problem of short bowel syndrome and associated 
liver failure is potentially manageable with multiorgan 
transplants he said 
williams has not performed any more multiorgan transplants 
although suitable patients would be accepted for consideration 
according to dr howard sankary a member of williams surgical team 
since the articles were written a fifth child died after 
multiple transplant surgery and starzl has suspended such 
operations until better antirejection medication is available 
the child fiveorgan recipient rolandrea dodge 3 of fruitland 
nm survived six weeks she died in january doctors believe she 
too died of cancer 
starzls team has had better luck with multiple organ abdominal 
transplants on adult patients with terminal cancer eleven of the 
first 13 have survived and are believed to be free of malignancy 
unlike the young multiorgan recipients the adults kept most of 
their own small intestines which the pittsburgh researchers said 
might explain the older patients success 
</TEXT>
