<TEXT>
americans took out 44 billion more in credit 
than they paid off in january as consumer debt grew at an annual 
rate of 79 percent the government reported thursday 
the federal reserve board said the january increase followed a 
revised increase of 43 billion in december and a gain of 47 
billion in november 
januarys rise in the seasonally adjusted rate of credit growth 
was up slightly from a 78 percent pace in december but below the 
85 percent rate in november 
the increase was held back by slower growth in auto loans and the 
category of debt that includes credit cards while loans for mobile 
homes increased after falling sharply in december 
consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic 
health since it accounts for twothirds of overall economic activity 
in january auto loans rose by 22 billion a 92 percent annual 
rate following a slightly larger 24 billion increase during 
december 
growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards also 
was weaker in january rising by 823 million or at a 53 percent 
annual rate that followed a december increase of 13 billion that 
represented an 84 percent rate of growth 
mobile home debts which had declined by 278 million in 
december rose by 82 million in january a 38 percent pace of 
growth 
bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by 
12 billion in january a 9 percent annual rate of growth after 
having risen 944 million or at a 69 percent pace in december 
overall total consumer debt reached a seasonally adjusted 6706 
billion in january up 84 percent from a year earlier 
