reservations reach into travel agencies and we were clearly 
successful in both of those objectives 
but the labor problem obviously took front stage and one of the 
reasons for that is a federal agency called the national mediation 
board that literally threw all pretense of neutrality to the wind 
kept eastern locked up in a fruitless destructive mediation process 
for 17 months while our losses grew alarmingly 
meanwhile some of our critics some of the union leaders engaged 
in what can only be described as a vicious vicious attack on the 
company and its management an organized litigation and 
disinformation campaign to smear the reputation of texas air of 
eastern and its management particularly frank lorenzo and to 
thwart our very efforts to provide working capital for the company 
through some liquidity programs 
you know if you step back the last several weeks have really 
seen the real issues at eastern airlines in my view unfortunately 
pushed to the background of the public debate instead some have 
framed the issues in large global terms almost defying rational 
boundaries 
they have tried to paint frank lorenzo who happens to be by 
the way the longest sitting ceo in the airline business today with 
16 continuous years in that role as some kind of corporate 
villain ignoring the fact that his efforts over the last 26 years 
in this business have created more aviation jobs than any other 
individual 
texas international in the early 1970s had 2500 employees and 
up until last week 60000 employees were under the texas air 
umbrella for those many years of building not destroying 
there has not been an honest debate of the issues that face 
eastern airlines for example the companys offer to the iam to 
guarantee all jobs for five years all jobs for five years to pay 
unskilled workers in a retraining program full pay while they get 
retrained to learn how to be technicians and mechanics so they could 
earn twice what theyre earning under the training program that 
hasnt been debated 
while trying to make this appear to be some kind of a national 
labor struggle between good and evil no one is even seriously 
debating the fact that the pilots union leadership decision to 
cripple the company defies rationality 
consider that their members average nearly 100000 a year in 
wages and benefits and the company proposed no reductions in base 
pay we proposed job guarantees for five years guarantees that 
there would be no sale of additional aircraft at eastern airlines 
that there would be protection on their pay in the event the company 
was not successful and had to seek reorganization under the 
bankruptcy laws 
this proposal from a company that in the last 10 years has lost 
one billion five hundred million dollars and that last year lost 
460 million 
the pilot union decision to ground easterns planes has been 
described i think accurately as professional suicide it almost 
defies explanation even in the context of a hard fought labor 
battle 
alpas leaders and financial adviser however have said publicly 
for some time that they are prepared for bankruptcy and in fact 
welcome actually welcome a bankruptcy process so that they could 
achieve their stated goal of seeking control of the airline 
the pilots union action has forced the bankruptcy filing they 
say they are prepared for but however prepared the financial 
adviser and the coterie of lawyers may be and the pilot union 
leaders whose salaries will continue how ever prepared they are for 
bankruptcy i wonder i wonder how prepared the eastern pilots and 
their families are for that process how prepared can those whose 
livelihood and standards of living and family security depend on 
flying easterns 200 plus airplanes most of which sit idle today 
how prepared can they be 
when the giddiness and emotional solidarity wears off and the 
picket line is no longer the selfdeluded battle between good and 
evil how will the real issues be resolved 
as a management not only with a personal stake in the outcome 
and im not ashamed to say a strong emotional attachment to this 
company but also with clear fiduciary obligations to the 
constituencies of the corporation including our investors including 
our creditors we tried mightily to keep eastern from bankruptcy 
but we also feel very strongly that we will be able to protect those 
interests of the creditors and those interests of investors and 
shareholders in the process that we have been driven to 
we expect and intend that all creditors will be fully safe that 
investors will realize a value and a fair return and that a 
restructured and revitalized although somewhat smaller eastern 
airlines will be flying and will be serving the traveling public for 
many years to come and most importantly to me at least is 
providing many more jobs to the eastern professional men and women 
who have had the cloud of failure hanging over their heads for many 
years and who have brought the airline in recent months to the 
number one position in ontime performance and i think theyll be 
able to do it again 
