a housesenate committee exploring rest home 
abuses viewed color slides of neglected residents thursday and 
heard gripping testimony from a survivor of a california home in 
which seven bodies were found buried in the yard 
rep claude pepper dfla released a report attributing 
problems at the homes in part to neglect by states and the decision 
about 25 years ago to move away from putting mentally ill persons 
into institutions 
pepper and the joint panel of the house and senate aging 
committees focused their attention on socalled board and care 
homes 
in different states the homes are called everything from rest 
homes group or personal care homes to domiciliaries they provide 
rooms meals and help with daily routines but not regular medical 
care such as provided by nursing homes 
john sharp 64 testified that he was a survivor of the 
unlicensed sacramento calif home run by dorothy puente seven 
bodies were found buried in puentes yard and she was charged last 
november with murder 
i often wonder why i was spared a terrible fate at the puente 
home sharp said 
he recalled seeing her going through residents mail and 
wondering why residents seemed to be disappearing from the home 
he said a pivotal moment came when he refused to allow her to 
begin receiving and cashing his government checks 
i told her that those checks were my lifeline and i couldnt 
trust them to anyone but myself i didnt turn over my social 
security checks to her and looking back thats probably what saved 
my life he said 
the report released by pepper was prepared by the house select 
committee on agings health subcommittee of which he is chairman 
many of the reports conclusions echoed those of a similar study 
released wednesday night by the general accounting office 
peppers report termed board and care homes a national 
tragedy 
we found that most of the one million elderly disabled and 
mentally ill persons who reside in board and care homes are being 
warehoused in understaffed underegulated shoddy and unsafe 
facilities pepper said 
the report identified many board and care residents as former 
state mental hospital inhabitants who were released in the 1960s as 
part of a push to place such patients in community settings 
the panel also heard a scratchy secretlyrecorded tape of an 
alabama board and care operator slapping a resident and describing 
how she had shot a woman for pulling her wig off 
the unidentified operator was described by jefferson county 
ala ombudsman julie oetting at the hearing as a convicted 
murderer 
earlier pepper 88 narrated slides of residents bound to 
wheelchairs and lying on floors and homes without proper fire 
safety equipment in maryland he said an owner continued to house 
11 residents in a burntout home without adequate fire safety 
equipment 
board and care homes typically serve many residents who rely on 
supplemental security income to pay the bills 
new jersey attorney david lazarus and rep james florio dnj 
used the analogy of a dog in a kennel to describe the lack of public 
commitment to rest home residents 
on average it costs 11 per day to board a 70pound dog in new 
jersey astonishingly new jersey board and care residents dependent 
upon ssi receive a low of 1130 to a high of just under 16 for 
their lodging meals and care in a board and care home florio 
said 
and in states that do not supplement the federal ssi amount 
the daily rates are even lower he said 
barbara jameson of the national association of residential care 
facilities said in an interview that she hoped the hearing would not 
convey the impression that the mistreatment was widespread 
i really dont believe there is widespread abuse she said 
i think there is far more abuse in biological families 
unfortunately than in licensed care homes 
