federal mediators on thursday denied an 
accusation by eastern airlines management that they had not been 
neutral in dealing with the company and its machinists union 
eastern president phil bates in a new york news conference after 
the company filed for protection from its creditors under bankruptcy 
laws accused the national mediation board of throwing all 
pretense of neutrality to the wind in trying to mediate the 
17month dispute 
after more than a year of talks with the airline and its 
international association of machinists and aerospace workers local 
the twomember board said it couldnt resolve the dispute and asked 
president bush to create an emergency panel that would have delayed 
a strike by up to 60 days bush refused and the machinists went on 
strike saturday 
bates accused the board of keeping the company locked up in a 
fruitless destructive mediation process while the airlines 
losses grew 
it is regrettable that easterns management made adverse 
comments about the board said charles r barnes the executive 
director of the board which mediates transportation industry labor 
disputes but im sure in hindsight that the parties will conclude 
that the board acted professionally impartially and in full 
accordance with the legal responsibilities 
in a statement the board said the dispute in which eastern 
originally asked for 200 million in salary cuts while the union 
sought 50 million in raises was one of the most complex the board 
has had to mediate since the airline industry was deregulated in 
1978 
easterns bankruptcy filing is unfortunate for the carrier its 
employees the traveling public and the nations transportation 
system the board said 
board spokesman david bushnell said mediators continued to talk 
with both the union and the company but had not managed to bring the 
two sides together since the walkout 
