<TEXT>
here is a summary of a speech given by 
cardinal joseph ratzinger president of the congregation for the 
doctrine of the faith at an extraordinary meeting of us bishops 
and vatican officials the summary was made available by the vatican 
in italian and translated into english by the associated press 
phrases in parentheses were added by the ap 
as the second vatican council lumen gentium 25 teaches us 
repeating a formula established by the council of trent the bishop 
is above all an evangelizer and in that way the actual successor of 
the apostles 
the image of the postconciliar second vatican council bishop 
has positive aspects today bishops preach more than in the past 
many bishops and episcopal conferences take positions with pastoral 
letters on great issues of the day offering a response in the light 
of faith 
less positive is the evolution of catechesis which is consigned 
in great measure to socalled experts 
even more thorny is the issue of the rapport between bishops and 
theologians who today have influence not only in the worlds of 
scientific research and university teaching but who also through 
the mass media bring into the public arena their often dissonant 
contributions to the point where their voices drown out those of 
the bishops who preach 
in many parts of the world theologians have taken the place of 
the bishop as teacher leading to a growing insecurity and 
disorientation 
after the second vatican council reflection on the primacy of 
the bishops mission of proclaiming the word has remained in 
practice without commentary 
instead one comes up against ideas aimed at limiting the bishop 
to the role of spiritual administrator 
these theories which come from the academic realm have 
transformed themselves into a kind of pressure on the bishop his 
role according to these theories would be to avoid polarization 
acting as a moderator in the plurality of different opinions 
the bishops have fully adapted themselves to this regulative 
model little defending their magisterial authority over 
theologians the preached word becomes seen as something merely 
pastoral and is not presented with the authority of decision 
and it ends up not even being truly pastoral because the pastoral 
approach consists of making people face decisions and confronting 
them with the authority of truth 
in addition according to theories of modern culture it is not 
possible to distinguish clearly between faith and theology and even 
if it could be done it would be the task only of the specialist 
the theologian but not of the shepherd bishop 
the most pressing question lies in the fact that the modern world 
distinguishes two spheres of life action and reflection the former 
according to theories of the modern world requires authority 
which is justified and useful at a functional level the second does 
not need authority because it follows solely the law of thought 
there is nothing definitive but only hypotheses still to be 
verified and tested 
the church according to these theories can exercise a 
functional authority in the sphere of its actions theology is not a 
matter of authority rather one of being professional this notion 
means that the church can certainly dispense pious advice but not 
proclaim the truth in a way that is binding and thereby call people 
to a commitment 
in addition in todays hierarchy of values individual liberties 
and the consequent rights of freedom of the mass media take the 
highest place while objective moral values on which there is 
anyway no agreement are banished to the private sphere not 
meriting any social and public protection 
bluntly one can say there is a right to immorality but morality 
has no rights the responsibility of witnessing to the truth of the 
gospel leads inevitably to passion for the truth here one finds 
also the positive conclusion of our reflection the hallmark of 
truth is that it is worth suffering for 
those who announce the gospel must also be martyrs in the most 
profound sense of the word 
</TEXT>
