<TEXT>
an army warrant officer who admitted receiving 
more than 100000 from 1983 to 1988 to provide classified military 
information to east germany and the soviet union was sentenced 
thursday to 40 years confinement and fined 50000 
warrant officer james w hall iii 30 of sharon springs ny 
showed no emotion as he was sentenced by col howard c eggers the 
military judge who presided at the courtmartial at fort mcnair here 
eggers also sentenced hall to a dishonorable discharge from the 
army and ordered him to forfeit all future pay and allowances 
hall who had pleaded guilty monday to 10 counts of espionage 
attempted espionage and failing to obey army regulations will be 
eligible for parole after serving a minimum of 10 years 
most of the governments case against hall including the details 
of his espionage activities was outlined for eggers during closed 
sessions of the courtmartial 
hall an intelligence analyst with a topsecret security 
clearance was arrested dec 21 near savannah ga and accused of 
delivering exposed film and documents dealing with communications 
intelligence and war plans to warsaw pact nations 
at the time of his arrest hall was assigned to the 24th infantry 
division and worked as an intelligence analyst at the armys g2 
intelligence section he joined the army in 1976 and spent most of 
his career in europe working as an analyst of intercepted radio and 
telephone traffic and coded messages 
col david armitage chief of the armys forensic psychiatry 
division at walter reed army hospital testified thursday that his 
examinations of hall suggested that hall was motivated primarily by 
money 
army prosecutors and defense lawyers agreed during the 
courtmartial that hall had received payments totaling between 
100000 and 200000 during the five years that he worked as a spy 
for east germany and the soviet union during part of that time he 
was on a 30000 per year retainer from east germany 
before leaving europe to return to the united states in 1987 
according to testimony hall received a medal and a 5000 bonus 
from the east german government 
after his arrest hall began cooperating with military 
authorities he entered into a pretrial agreement in which he 
volunteered to submit to unlimited debriefings and polygraph 
examinations about his spy activities 
he also agreed to testify if called against huseyin yildirim a 
turkishborn naturalized citizen to whom hall allegedly passed the 
intelligence information 
yildirim 60 was arrested at his home is belleair beach fla 
last december and charged with conspiracy to commit espionage by 
giving agents of a foreign government national defense secrets if 
convicted he could be sentenced to life in prison 
the pretrial agreement prohibited the army from seeking the death 
penalty against hall it also included an agreement which eggers 
was not permitted to see until after sentencing that set halls 
maximum sentence at 45 years confinement 
