<TEXT>
american universities once publicized 
themselves discreetly on pennants and tshirts sold in local campus 
stores now theyre doing it for lucrative royalties on items 
ranging from fishing lures to toilet seats sold at some of the 
nations biggest retailers 
the explosion in collegiate merchandise reflects a rising demand 
for products bearing hawkeyes buckeyes lions tigers bears and 
other school symbols a partial consequence of the enormous 
television exposure collegiate sports teams are getting nowadays 
estimated annual retail sales of such items exceeds 1 billion 
its not just in college bookstores anymore its in k mart 
sears and penneys said kim allan manager of university 
licensing programs at michigan state 
collegiate merchandise sales have doubled in the last five years 
and now nearly equal combined sales of national football league and 
major league baseball products said bill battle president and 
owner of atlantabased collegiate concepts inc 
collegiate concepts and international collegiate enterprises of 
los angeles through a joint venture handle the licensing 
arrangement for 100 schools 
universities license products bearing their names or logos known 
as marks and receive royalties in return 
battle said soft goods such as tshirts sweatshirts and caps 
account for between 80 percent and 85 percent of the collegiate 
merchandise but novelty items have flourished 
in 1981 the university of georgia licensed a local discount 
retail chain to sell a bulldog tarantula the spider had red and 
black markings matching the schools colors and sported a tiny felt 
bulldog cap 
i dont know how they did with it said avery mclean 
director promotions and licensing at georgia 
penn state university has licensed a nittany lion swimming pool 
liner iowa has approved a hawkeye fishing lure nebraska go big 
red boxer shorts and michigan state a spartan toilet seat 
the university of california at los angeles began the first major 
licensing program in 1974 
many other university followed suit in the early 1980s to get 
marketing control over their names and logos which had started 
appearing on products that either were too embarrasing or posed a 
liability threat 
one company approached penn state last year hoping to make a 
nittany lion casket with the universitys mascot embroidered 
inside the lid 
that was thought to be in bad taste said o jean barrett 
coordinator of penn states office of licensing programs 
university standards differ but most refuse licenses to 
companies making products relating to alcohol tobacco and firearms 
besides gaining better control over their monikers university 
licensing programs have provided the schools with a large source of 
income 
royalties now total more than 500000 a year at several larger 
universities with nationally known football or basketball teams 
penn state which has one of the the largest licensing 
operations has earned 430000 in the first 6 months of the current 
fiscal year for use in scholarship funds up 8 percent from the 
previous year said roger williams a university spokesman 
collegiate merchandise also has been a boon to department stores 
three years ago jc penney co started team sports shops in 
500 branches said peter mcgrath division merchandise manager for 
athletic apparel and footware for the department store 
business at the shops has grown 30 percent a year reflecting an 
increase demand for college and pro merchandise mcgrath said 
a number of universities have started exploring markets in japan 
canada and europe ucla with the largest foreign program already 
sells about 9 million to 10 million worth of goods annually in 
japan 
we have a tremendous appeal in japan because were west 
coast said jack rovoyr a ucla product licensing official 
were california were sunshine ucla is more than a university 
its a lifestyle 
</TEXT>
