<TEXT>
soviet doctors overwhelmed by earthquake 
casualties in devastated armenia did the best they could with 
schoolboy karen kocharians crushed hand american doctors hoped to 
finish the job with complex microsurgery in this second story in an 
intermittent series tracing karens progress associated press 
reporter bruce rule describes agonizing hours inside the operating 
room and details the surgerys results 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the boy had told everyone im going to get 
my hand back 
now far from his home in armenia where an earthquake three 
months ago maimed his right hand karen kocharian waited with his 
father to be taken to the operating room for a transplant of toes 
for missing fingers the 9yearold grew quiet and withdrawn 
when doctors came to prepare karen his father sarkis carried 
the boy from the bed to the stretcher the interpreter hadnt 
arrived so the doctors tried using hand signs to explain what was 
happening karen and his father didnt understand 
sarkis kocharian tried to keep the boy calm but karen who also 
lost his left eye in the quake kept remembering operations in the 
soviet union every time he had gone into the operating room he 
came out with something missing 
normally a stoic man the father turned away several times and 
wiped tears from his eyes once or twice he sat and covered his head 
ahead was another long operation karens first since project 
hope brought him and 36 other young armenians to us hospitals for 
special treatment 
dr lee osterman director of hand surgery at childrens hospital 
of philadelphia estimated an 8hour operation 
it was not to be 
the first four hours were routine the veins and arteries being 
labelled and the second and third toes on the left foot amputated in 
one piece osterman said the missing toes would not affect karens 
ability to walk or to play his favorite game soccer 
after attaching the toe bones to the hand with pins osterman 
wheeled a highpowered microscope over to begin microsurgery 
he used a piece of vein from the foot to bridge the gap between a 
major hand artery which had been damaged in the quake and one in 
the transplanted toes the attachment completed osterman waited for 
the blood to flow into the new toefingers 
it didnt 
the pulse is there but its dying somewhere north of the thumb 
once it is hooked together it either flows or it doesnt osterman 
said 
he held up a closed fist to illustrate we like it to boom 
hook it up and it goes boom he said quickly opening his fingers 
the blockage could be simple spasms causing the vessels to 
contract because theyre cold osterman said or something inside in 
the vessel 
this is where the technique leaves and the luck begins he 
said 
estimating where the blockage might be in the artery he cut the 
vessel closer to the wrist blood spurted spitting two three feet 
onto the floor 
a second vein was used to reattach the arteries osterman said 
he could feel a thrill a pulse to the toefingers but not 
enough its not providing sufficient flow 
the operating room telephone rang a nurse said karens father 
was asking why the operation was taking so long it was 730 pm 
three hours after he thought it should have ended 
osterman went out to talk with kocharian and george ohanian a 
soviet immigrant storekeeper whose family is acting as host to the 
boy and his father 
hes fine the doctor said showing on his own hand what had 
been done inside ohanian translated it will be three maybe four 
more hours 
kocharian smiled slightly politely then nodded and looked down 
to the floor ohanian had been walking him through the halls since 
morning if we sit he begins to ask why its taking so long 
other armenian parents and armenianamerican helpers gathered 
around kocharian offering silent support albert zamanian whose 
17yearold daughter armenuhi was being treated for crushed arms 
gave him a set of middle eastern worry beads called tesbik 
kocharian absently fondled the yellow beads repeating over and 
over peace love god 
it was now 830 pm back in the operating room one of the 
assistants leaned over to osterman the assistants car was in a 
garage that closes at midnight osterman did not turn from the 
microscope 
better move it 
by 1100 pm osterman had almost completed attaching the toes 
vein to the hand when blood started flowing through the new 
appendages 
were getting a little but its still too white we want pink 
toes 
as the vein was completely attached the flow increased but the 
blood was not traveling through the toes properly 
the doctors talked and decided to close the wound and wait to 
see if the circulation improved they wrapped the hand leaving the 
toefingers sticking through the gauze 
it was shortly after midnight more than 16 hours after the 
operation began when osterman went to find karens father 
kocharian watched as the surgeon explained to ohanian what had 
happened throwing the best possible light on the operations 
chances 
leading the men down a hall near the recovery room osterman 
stopped the doctors pushing karens stretcher a doctor touched 
karens face and his eyes opened 
his father looked down smiled and nodded the boys eyes closed 
and kocharian broke down and turned to the wall sobbing in relief 
within days of the march 3 surgery karen had recovered enough to 
ask for his favorite american food corned beef sandwiches he also 
ate an armenian treat strawberries and watched monster movies on 
television 
circulation in the transplanted toes however had not increased 
last tuesday osterman operated again stripping the skin from 
the toefingers and inserting them into a flap of skin in the groin 
area karens hand will remain attached there for a month as the 
capillaries in the skin flap graft naturally to the hand 
the flap will then be cut away leaving only a scar and will be 
cut between the toes so the boy will have two fingers to work 
against his thumb 
his father shook his head after the second operation i am not 
convinced i am not sure that this is all over now that this 
one will work 
