<TEXT>
the major commercial television networks are 
pointing to the merger pact between time inc and warner 
communications inc to support their campaign for relaxed federal 
regulation of program ownership 
but independent television stations who have become a much 
stronger competitor for the abc cbs and nbc networks in recent 
years say deregulation would unfairly skew the competition for 
programming in favor of the networks 
one of the motivations cited for the timewarner combination was 
an interest in keeping pace with what is quickly becoming a global 
market for media and entertainment companies 
time a leader in magazine publishing cable networks and cable 
system operations has the potential to provide more outlets for 
warners entertainment production units including its movie and 
television studios 
the networks say they share the ambition to compete in the global 
marketplace but are hamstrung by a court decree limiting the amount 
of primetime programming they may produce and federal regulations 
forbidding them from having a financial interest in the other shows 
they run 
the timewarner agreement is a vivid example of how greatly the 
