<TEXT>
eastern airlines bankruptcy filing threw 
members of congress into confusion today just as they were set to 
work on legislation that would force a reluctant president bush to 
temporarily halt the crippling strike against the carrier 
the house public works and transportation committee had planned 
to approve the legislation today and send it for a vote to the full 
house next week where passage with the overwhelming support of the 
majority democrats would be expected 
but the panel postponed its meeting at least until midafternoon 
when lawmakers received word that the ailing airline had filed for 
protection from creditors in us bankruptcy court in new york 
rep james oberstar dminn chairman of the public works and 
transportation aviation subcommittee and other members of the panel 
said there were concerns that legislation dealing with one specific 
company involved in bankruptcy proceedings might be unconstitutional 
they said they believed that under the law bankruptcy 
legislation must be applied uniformly not just to one company they 
also said they believed the problem could be resolved 
i think we can sort this out oberstar told reporters 
but oberstar and rep glenn anderson dcalif chairman of the 
full committee offered no specifics when asked how the bankruptcy 
proceedings might cause the legislation to be changed 
there may be some amendments anderson said 
the legislation approved tuesday along party lines by the 
aviation subcommittee would require bush to appoint an emergency 
board to review the differences between eastern and the 
international association of machinists which represents 8500 
machinists baggage handlers and other ground workers 
the strikers would return to work for up to 60 days while the 
board studied the dispute which is largely over wages and benefits 
and recommended a solution 
the carriers pilots and flight attendants have honored the 
machinists picket lines forcing eastern to terminate most of its 
1040 daily flights 
