<TEXT>
the mexican government has decided to sell its 
controlling interest in the nations problemridden telephone 
company despite strong union opposition government and union 
sources said thursday 
such a sale would be the most dramatic example to date of 
president carlos salinas de gortaris efforts to privatize 
governmentowned companies and modernize the mexican economy 
the problem is to do it without making it sound like another 
confrontation with a labor union a government source told the 
associated press the timing of an announcement is uncertain 
the government specifically salinas has told us there is no 
alternative said a telephone workers union official the union 
strongly opposes the move he said 
both officials said they could not allow their names to be used 
because the two sides are now engaged in talks 
there is a campaign against the union against corruption 
against the union members the end of this campaign is the 
privatization of the company the union official said he said 
government proposals would require changes in 51 union contracts 
one for each department of the company 
salinas who jailed corrupt leaders of the oil workers union in 
january does not want to get an image as a union buster the 
government source said 
but if we are going to modernize the phone company we need new 
technology and more investments and some changes in unionmanagement 
relations the source added 
telefonos de mexico as the company is called has nearly 50000 
employees although the union is controlled by the ruling 
institutional revolutionary party the government has had to 
intervene at least twice in recent years to prevent strikes 
the government owns 51 percent of the company and another 10 
percent is held in the socalled mexico fund which is traded on the 
new york stock exchange stockbroker guillermina ortiz said the 
stock is fluctuating on the mexico exchange because of sale rumors 
but that it would definitely go much higher if the company is sold 
it closed at 31 cents a share on wednesday 
union head francisco hernandez juarez has accused the government 
of trying to sell out the telephone company and fears privatization 
would lead to a reduction in union membership because of dismissals 
this week hernandez complained that telephone company proposals 
were evidence of evil intentions toward the union 
government officials admit the company has a bad image that 
reflects on the government 
it is known for poor service and high rates and even before 
salinas was elected stories circulated of his disgust with the 
systems inefficiencies and his admiration for the way chile 
improved its system privatization 
in a governmentsponsored 1987 poll 13 percent of respondents 
said telmex was the worstadministered company in the public sector 
56 percent said they had found mysterious longdistance calls on 
their bills without explanation 
getting a line repaired can take months although one shortcut is 
to locate and independently hire a telephone company crew that might 
happen to be in the neighborhood employees often complain of low 
salaries they earn an average of about 14 a day in spite of the 
high rates charged by the company 
installing a telephone on unwired premises costs nearly 800 in 
mexico city as against an average of 120 in new york a heavily 
taxed threeminute phone call to new york costs 750 while the 
return phone call would cost 510 
the union started when more people were needed than are needed 
now the government source said the government says the company 
is overstaffed and accuses the union of sabotage when it doesnt get 
what it wants but the union official denied that 
the problem is outdated equipment and lack of financing 
telefonos needs 14 billion to modernize and become competitive we 
think the government should get the money the official said 
the government source said salinas hopes to turn the telephone 
company around the way it did the staterun and moneylosing airline 
aeromexico when the union went on strike last year the airline was 
declared bankrupt and was eventually sold with employee unions 
buying a minority share 
