<TEXT>
gov judd gregg announced wednesday that the 
state will ask a federal bankruptcy judge to block lowpower testing 
of the seabrook nuclear power plant 
the move is a stunning reversal of policy for the state of new 
hampshire which has officially supported the project for 17 years 
lead seabrook owner public service company of new hampshire 
sought bankruptcy protection in january 1988 because of licensing 
delays the 59 billion project was completed in july 1986 but 
remains idle because of evacuationplanning and financial obstacles 
in a statement gregg said the state will argue to the bankruptcy 
judge that letting seabrook conduct atomic tests is not sound 
business judgment unless it has first obtained the clearances 
necessary to begin fullpower operation including final evacuation 
plans 
if seabrook never goes online commercially then lowpower 
testing will have been a wasted exercise the resultant 
contamination will have been avoidable and the expense will have 
been unnecessary the republican governor said 
consistent with this position i have elected to petition the 
federal bankruptcy court to prevent seabrook from conducting such 
tests a motion to this effect will be filed within the next two 
weeks gregg said 
a seabrook spokesman rob williams said gregg must be 
misinformed and that prompt testing of the reactor is prudent 
project officials hope to start the tests within weeks 
nicholas ashooh a spokesman for lead seabrook owner public 
service company of new hampshire said company officials have 
concerns that this may lead to additional unnecessary delays and 
cost increases for seabrook and may further delay our getting 
seabrooks power which we need 
in december the nuclear regulatory commission said seabrook may 
start lowpower tests when the plants owners prove they can come up 
with 721 million to decommission the reactor if it conducts the 
tests but never operates commercially 
seabrook owners initially hoped to give that assurance in 
january in the form of a surety bond but they have yet to do so 
public service owns 36 percent of seabrook and gregg said the 
state opposes letting the company take on what he estimated as an 
additional 25 million liability for lowpower decommissioning 
a company in bankruptcy should not voluntarily accept 
additional liabilities gregg said 
gregg also said that contaminating seabrook with atomic testing 
will needlessly render the facility useless for alternate 
applications 
